ing at early stages of state building has led to chronic fiscal instability and weakened state capacity in the developing world.Drawing on a wealth of original data to document the rise of cheap overseas credit between 1816 and 1913, Didac Queralt shows how countries in the global periphery obtained these loans by agreeing to “extreme conditionality,” which empowered international investors to take control of local revenue sources in cases of default, and how foreclosure eroded a country’s tax base and caused lasting fiscal disequilibrium. Queralt goes on to combine quantitative analysis of tax performance between 1816 and 2005 with qualitative historical analysis in Latin America, Asia, Africa, and the Middle East, illustrating how overreliance on external capital by local leaders distorts their incentives to expand tax capacity, articulate power sharing institutions, and strengthen bureaucratic apparatus.Panoramic in scope, Pawned States sheds needed light on how early and easy access to external finance pushes developing nations into trajectories characterized by fragile fiscal institutions and autocratic politics.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mai 2023) 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Geopolitics.2bisacsh  aAsset.  aAusterity.  aBalance of trade.  aBaring crisis.  aBen Ansell.  aBond (finance).  aBond market.  aBowring Treaty.  aCapital control.  aCapital market.  aCold War (1985–91).  aColonial war.  aComparative advantage.  aConditionality.  aConsumer debt.  aCorporate tax.  aCredit (finance).  aCredit crunch.  aCreditor.  aCurrency.  aDebt relief.  aDebt restructuring.  aDebt.  aDefault (finance).  aDevelopmental state.  aDollar diplomacy.  aEconomic interventionism.  aEconomics.  aEconomy.  aEurocurrency Market.  aExchange rate.  aExpense.  aExport subsidy.  aExte